  MAMABOLO condemned the shooting at Bosman Taxi Rank in Tshwane on Friday. The Gauteng MEC for Public Transport and Roads Infrastructure, Jacob Mamabolo, said the shooting left five people injured and one critically. According to Mamabolo, the preliminary report by police indicated that a shooting incident took place at a taxi rank, leaving two operators and three commuters injured. "The injured were rushed to hospital for medical attention and there were fatalities recorded.” he said He added that there were different ways available to resolve conflict without resorting to violence. “Violence has never resolved any conflict; it is an act of criminality. "Innocent lives, especially those of passengers are placed at risk,” he said He called on those involved in this nefarious act to exercise restraint and engage each other in finding amicable solutions to their differences. He also said government has platforms readily available in finding long-lasting solutions. "The reasons for the shootings are not yet known," he said. Mamabolo appealed to those with information to come forward and help law enforcement agencies in bringing those responsible for this senseless act to book. Gauteng Police spokesman Captain Kay Makhubele said five victims, two taxi operators and three commuters were injured and rushed to hospital for medical attention after shooting incident. He said information is still sketchy at this point, but police can confirm that two unknown suspects arrived at the taxi rank, on foot and fired shots indiscriminately. "No fatalities have been reported at this stage and police have launched a search for the suspects," he said. Makhubele said police are appealing to anyone who may have witnessed the incident to call the crime stop number 08600 10111 or contact police at Pretoria Central South African Police Service.